          "body": "Paul stacks four perfectly paired participial antitheses (vv. 8-9): *afflicted but not crushed, perplexed but not despairing, persecuted but not forsaken, struck down but not destroyed.* The Greek pairs play on cognates and rhyme — *aporoumenoi all' ouk exaporoumenoi* (perplexed but not utterly perplexed) — to make the paradox memorable. Then in vv. 10-11 Paul interprets the paradoxes: he is *always carrying about in the body the dying of Jesus, so that the life of Jesus also may be manifested in our body.* The cruciform pattern is not accidental affliction overcome by spiritual resources — it is the deliberate participation in the death of Jesus that becomes the means by which the resurrection life of Jesus is displayed. And v. 12 lands the pastoral point: *death works in us, but life in you.* Apostolic suffering is congregational gain."
